title: Trump promise $2000 tariff dividend for Americans, calling those against tariffs ‘FOOLS’
description: US President Donald Trump has vowed to pay a dividend of at least $US2,000 per person from tariffs on foreign goods.  The announcement came via Truth Social on Sunday.  The president did not clarify who would be eligible to receive the dividend, but hinted that high-income individuals would not qualify.  Trump comments come as the Supreme Court deliberates the legality of the president’s ability to impose sweeping tariffs.

title: Dire warnings that Schumer’s government shutdown could crash the US economy as a deal emerges
description: The US government shutdown led by Chuck Schumer is dragging on into its 40th day and people are really starting to feel it.

title: ‘Reality is offensive’: BBC presenter reprimanded for pointing out left’s ‘stupidity’ on gender
description: Sky News host James Macpherson discusses BBC presenter Martine Croxall being reprimanded and “convicted of a face crime” after she corrected her autocue from ‘pregnant people’ to ‘women’ live on air.  “This is what happens when the woke run the asylum: you can say whatever you like, as long as it’s exactly what they tell you to say,” he said.  “Personally, I thought Croxall’s expression was magnificent ... The BBC shouldn’t have reprimanded her; they should have promoted her.  “She pointed out the stupidity of the progressive left with nothing but a raised eyebrow.”

title: Chris Minns in limelight after MPs call for a ‘change’ in youth crime laws
description: NSW Nationals MP Michael Kemp urges NSW Premier Chris Minns to provide a “change in the law” for youth offenders.  “We need to see a consequence,” Mr Kemp said.  “We need them to go into robust community programs that are diverting them away from the justice system.  “We need to see that law change to protect our community and to make sure that we can feel safe in our own homes.”

title: Chris Minns urged to stop giving youth offenders a ‘slap on the wrist’
description: NSW Nationals MP Michael Kemp claims there is “far too much” youth crime in Sydney.  Mr Kemp said there are “no consequences” for youth offenders currently.  “We are seeing a slap on the wrist and a revolving door,” he said.  “We are asking the Premier to stop that revolving door.”

title: ‘If they get this wrong, they lose a leader’: Liberals to decide net zero position
description: Bondi Partners Senior Advisor Peter McGauran claims the Liberals are facing an “existential crisis” amid debate over the party’s climate policy.  Threats of resignation and rebellion hang over a series of meetings where the Coalition will thrash out its position on net zero this week.  “I think it’s arguably the most important week in the history of the Liberal Party because if they get this wrong, they lose a leader, perhaps not immediately but within the next few months,” Mr McGauran told Sky News Australia.  “And if the policy’s wrong, they will go backwards at the next election and lose more seats.”

title: ‘Great step forward’: NSW government announces $23 million package to combat youth crime
description: NSW Nationals MP Michael Kemp says the state government’s announcement of a $23 million package for youth crime is a “good step in the right direction”.  “It’s a great step forward,” Mr Kemp said.  “I thank the police minister, I’ve been asking for it for months and months and months.  “We need money that comes into the town to be accountable.  “These diversionary programs … they need to give kids employability skills, something that they can be proud of.”

title: People in Kempsey remain ‘on edge’ due to the ‘increase’ in youth crime
description: NSW Nationals MP Michael Kemp comments on the rise of crime in the town of Kempsey, claiming people in the community feel “on edge”.  “We’ve seen an increase in crime,” Mr Kemp said.  “We’ve seen the erosion of the Australian values.  “Social media at the moment, it’s increasing the notoriety of crime.”

title: Chris Minns pushed to ‘come down hard’ on neo-Nazi protesters
description: NSW Nationals MP Michael Kemp comments on the neo-Nazi protest in Sydney on Saturday.  “I don’t think 60 people out of five million represent Sydney,” Mr Kemp said.  “The Premier really needs to come down hard on those members.”

title: US Senate holds rare Sunday session as 40-day government shutdown nears resolution
description: The US Senate has convened for a rare Sunday session amid reports the 40-day government shutdown is about to end.

title: TV host reacts to Russell Crowe’s ‘embarrassing’ interview with Joe Rogan
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi has slammed actor Russell Crowe for his “embarrassing” comments on Joe Rogan’s podcast about Australian politics.

title: Keir Starmer effigy burns as he faces tremendous backlash for state of UK
description: UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer has become the latest figure to appear as a giant effigy at a town’s Bonfire Night celebrations.  The effigy, depicting Starmer as a “farmer harmer”, saw him wearing a hat and collar as well as a clipboard that said “suck up to Trump” written in big letters.  The farmer note was a nod to farming communities that slammed his decision on inheritance tax.  The Edenbridge Bonfire Society’s annual celebration pokes fun at “infamous celebrities” and has been going on for more than 30 years.  Previous targets include former UK Prime Minister Liz Truss, Ticketmaster and Oasis, as well as Boris Johnson.

title: ‘Wasn’t playing’: TV host praises Sydney Sweeney’s handling of GQ interview
description: Sky News Australia host James Morrow has slammed GQ for making everything “political” during their interview with Sydney Sweeney.

title: State funeral to be held for the late Graham Richardson
description: A state funeral will be held for former Labor senator Graham Richardson, who tragically passed away at the age of 76.

title: ‘Shocking error’: ABC must be held accountable following doctored documentary scandal
description: Liberal Senator Sarah Henderson stresses the importance of accountability at the ABC following a scandal involving a doctored documentary.  “The doctoring of the vision in relation to Heston Russell and the false claims essentially that he was a war criminal were an absolute disgrace,” Ms Henderson told Sky News Australia.  “Heads should have rolled. That was a shocking error by the ABC. It did look, in part, deliberate.  “I’m a strong advocate for a rewrite of the ABC act.”
